ity. Writing immediately after the war and examining only those critical months of 1944 when Hitler's Germany occupied its ally Hungary, Erno Munkácsi describes the Judenrat's desperation and fear as it attempted to prevent the looming catastrophe, agonized over decisions not made, and struggled to grasp the immensity of a tragedy that would take the lives of 427,000 Hungarian Jews in the very last year of the Second World War. This long-overdue translation makes available Munkácsi's profound and unparalleled insight into the Holocaust in Hungary, revealing the "choiceless choices" that confronted members of the Judenrat forced to execute the Nazis' orders. With an in-depth introduction, a brief biography of Erno Munkácsi, ample annotations by László Csosz and Ferenc Laczó, two dozen archival photographs, and detailed maps, How It Happened is an essential resource for historians and students of the Holocaust, the Second World War, and Central Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)-Hungary-Personal narratives. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBalikó Lengyel, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsősz, Ferenc Laczó and László, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCsősz, László, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaczó, Ferenc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunk, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunk, Nina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMunkácsi, Ernő, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPapp, Susan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831112736